Weinberger v. Romero-Barcelo
Supreme Court of the United States
February 23, 1982, Argued ; April 27, 1982, Decided 
No. 80-1990 
Reporter
456 U.S. 305 *; 102 S. Ct. 1798 **; 72 L. Ed. 2d 91 ***; 1982 U.S. LEXIS 34 ****; 50 U.S.L.W. 4434; 12 ELR 20538; 17 ERC (BNA) 1217WEINBERGER, SECRETARY OF DEFENSE, ET AL. v. ROMERO-BARCELO ET AL.
Prior History:  [****1]  CERTIORARI TO THE UNITED STATES COURT OF APPEALS FOR THE FIRST CIRCUIT.  
Disposition:  643 F.2d 835, reversed and remanded.  
Core Terms



injunction, district court, pollutants, discharges, compliance, waters, equitable discretion, exemption, public interest, enjoin, cases, violations, injunctive relief, balancing, endangered species, statutory scheme, federal court, equitable, statutory violation, court of equity, cessation, island, violation of law, agencies, remedies, withhold, permits, darter, snail, exercise of discretion
Case Summary




Procedural Posture
Petitioners, government officials, sought certiorari review of the order of the United States Court of Appeals for the First Circuit vacating the district court's order denying respondents, officials and residents of Puerto Rico, an injunction, under the Federal Water Pollution Control Act, 33 U.S.C.S. § 1251 et seq., to prevent petitioners from discharging pollutants into navigable waters.
Overview
Respondents, officials and residents of Puerto Rico, brought an action against petitioners, government officials, under the Federal Water Pollution Control Act (FWPCA), 33 U.S.C.S. § 1251 et seq., to stop the discharge of ordnance into the waters surrounding Puerto Rico. The district court found that respondents had violated the FWPCA by discharging the ordnance without a permit and ordered respondents to obtain a permit. The district court denied injunctive relief. The circuit court vacated the district court's order, with instructions to issue injunctive relief. The court reversed the circuit court's order. At the outset, the court ruled that the circuit court erred in concluding that the district court was without authority to provide relief short of an injunction. The statutory scheme of the FWPCA, including a phased compliance scheme, and limitations on injunctions, suggested that the district had discretion in addressing violations. Moreover, the court ruled that in the present case, where the discharge was not found to have polluted the waters, the violation could be resolved by the less restrictive remedy of requiring petitioners to secure the proper permit.
Outcome
The court reversed the circuit court's order vacating the district court's order denying respondents, officials and residents of Puerto Rico, an injunction because the district court had authority to issue an appropriate remedy that was less restrictive than an injunction. The court remanded for further proceedings.
